DENGNGEG.eng_example: Listen to what they are saying.

DENGNGEG.ilok_example: Indiak nga mangngeg ti boses mo.

DENGNGEP.definition: to apply ointment, poultice and the like (to an injury).

DEPPA.definition: span or distance measured by both arms extended sideways.
to measure by the two arms extended sideways.

DEPPAAG.eng_example: Three houses collapsed after the fire.
DEPPAAG.ilok_example: Tallo nga balay ti dimpaag kalpasan ti uram.

DEPPAAG.definition: to cause to collapse or topple.
DEPPAAG.eng_example: The wind won’t cause your fence to collapse for it is strong.
DEPPAAG.ilok_example: Saan nga deppaagen ti angin dayta abulog yo ta nalagda.

DEPPEL.definition: to imprint or put one’s thumbprint.
to press on, apply pressure on.

DEPPES.definition: to cause to bend backward; to push down or close to the surface.

DERDER.definition: to cause to become pulpy by beating, cooking, etc.
to become pulpy due to beating, overcooking, etc.

DESDES.definition: to be streaked with, have trails of.

DI.definition: a particle expressing indifference, defiance or encouragement.
DI.eng_example: Then elope (with someone) if that is what you want to do. var. of DAYDI. var. of IDI.
DI.ilok_example: Di makitaray ka no isu ti kayat mo.

DIABLES.definition: form of DIABLO used in cursing.
DIABLES.eng_example: That devil Paul is indeed very lucky.
DIABLES.ilok_example: Naggaset ket ti diables nga Paulon.

DIARYO.definition: appear or be published in a newspaper.

DIASKE.definition: a curse word synonymous with DIABLES; devil.
DIASKE.ilok_example: Kasla napukaw nga asok ti diaske.

DIAYA.definition: to offer, give or present as an act of worship or devotion.
DIAYA.eng_example: He offered all his properties in order to help them.
DIAYA.ilok_example: Indiaya na amin nga kukua na nga pangtulong kadakuada.

DIDIGRA.eng_example: We were scared during the past war.
DIDIGRA.ilok_example: Nadidigra kami itay napalabas nga gerra.

DIDING.definition: to provide with a wall, put a wall to.
DIDING.eng_example: We will put a wall to our house tomorrow.
DIDING.ilok_example: Didingan mi daytoy balay mi inton bigat.

DIGO.definition: 1. broth; the liquid of a dish. 2. coconut water.

PADIGO.eng_example: It was he who shared us some of his food.

PADIGO.definition: to share (a portion of one’s food) (with another).
PADIGO.eng_example: He shared with me much of his food.

DIGOS.definition: to take a bath, to bathe oneself.
DIGOS.eng_example: They are going to take a bath in the river.

DIGOS.definition: to give (a person or animal) a bath, to bathe (a person or animal).
DIGOS.eng_example: They are going to bathe their water buffalo in the brook.
DIGOS.ilok_example: Mapan da digosen diay nuang da idiay waig.

DIKEN.definition: pad: a circlet of cloth placed on top of the head on which a load is set; this protects the crown of the head from injury and at the same time stabilizes the load.

DIKET.definition: 1. sticky or glutinous rice. 2. sticky variety of corn, 3. sticky variety of cassava.

DIKIDIK.eng_example: He will grind that toasted rice into powder.
DIKIDIK.ilok_example: Dikidiken na dayta nakirog nga bagas.

DIKKI.definition: soft deposit on the surface of the teeth, as when one does not brush his teeth.

DIKORASION.definition: to decorate or adorn with, to use as decoration.

DILAMUT.definition: to (be able to) gather with difficulty from a scant supply; to scrape; to benefit or be given a share of something that is scant or meager.
DILAMUT.eng_example: We were not given a share of the money that he gave.
DILAMUT.ilok_example: Awan ti nadilamutan mi ti daydiay inted na nga kuarta.

DILAP.definition: to flood, inundate; to have a flood.
to stick out one’s tongue at someone.
to stick out one’s tongue at (someone).
DILAP.eng_example: It was he at whom he stuck out his tongue.

DILDIL.ilok_example: Saan mo nga dildilan dayta pinggan.

DILI.eng_example: He knows the stony stretch of the road.
DILI.ilok_example: Ammo na ti nadili nga paset ti dalan.

DILIG.definition: to compare (to someone or something). syn. (dial.) of SIBUG.

DILLAW.definition: to notice, observe, see, perceive; hence, 2. to call attention to, remark or comment on; to criticize, complain about.
DILLAW.eng_example: Don’t notice or make any comment on his manner of eating.
DILLAW.ilok_example: Saan mo nga dildillawen ti pannangan na.

DILLAW.definition: to notice or observe by chance; to perceive.
DILLAW.eng_example: I noticed by chance that the young man wants to say something.
DILLAW.ilok_example: Nadlaw ko nga adda kayat na nga ibaga diay baro.

PADLAW.definition: to cause someone to notice or perceive; to show, reveal, display.

DINNA.definition: to put or place oneself at the side of, to go and stay at the side of.
DINNA.eng_example: Don’t go and stay at the side of my daughter.
DINNA.ilok_example: Saan mo nga dinnaan dayta balasang ko.

DINGPIL.eng_example: Squeeze those sour fruits so as to remove their juice.
DINGPIL.ilok_example: Dingpilen yo dagita pias tapno maikkat ti tubbog na.

DINGO.definition: to take care of, to feed.
DINGO.eng_example: It was he who fed the pig.

DINGOEN.definition: animals, especially hogs, raised for meat.

DIPAS.eng_example: The bananas were consumed in a short time.

DIPPIG.definition: a kind of banana which is flat in shape.
DIPPIG.ilok_example: It is usually boiled or fried before it is eaten.

DIPPIT.eng_example: Don’t press near those who are working.
DIPPIT.ilok_example: Saan ka nga dumippit kadagita agtartarabaho.

DIPPIT.eng_example: The people were pressed together due to the great number of those who went to see the show.
DIPPIT.ilok_example: Uray la nga agdidipiit ti tao ti kaadu ti nagbuya.
Saan mo nga dippiten dayta badok.

DIRAM-US.eng_example: As soon as you wake up wash your face.
Wash the face of your brother (or sister) when he (or she) wakes up.
DIRAM-US.ilok_example: Diram-usam dayta kabsat mo intono makariing.

DISGRASIA.definition: 1. to inflict injury on, to cause to have an accident or misfortune. 2. to assault or molest sexually.
1. to meet a misfortune or accident, to be injured. 2. to be assaulted or molested sexually.

DISKURSO.definition: to make a speech or oration.

DISMAYA.definition: to be upset, perturbed, discomposed, distressed.

DISNOG.definition: to hit with the fists; to punch.

DISSAAG.definition: to get down or off, alight, descend, dismount.
to take, put or place down from a higher place.

DISSAAR.definition: to put or place on the floor.
DISSAAR.eng_example: Place that child on the floor.

DISSO.eng_example: They first showed the beautiful spots in the Philippines.
DISSO.ilok_example: Immuna nga impabuya da dagiti napintas nga disso ditoy Pilipinas.

DISSO.definition: to alight, to set (on a place), to land.
DISSO.eng_example: The bird alighted on my shoulder.

DISSOOR.definition: to cause to fall suddenly and heavily, to put down suddenly and heavily.
DISSOOR.eng_example: It was he who put down the big box suddenly and heavily.
DISSOOR.ilok_example: Isu ti nangidissoor ti dakkel nga kahon.

DISTURBO.eng_example: Please don’t disturb me for I have much work to do.
DISTURBO.ilok_example: Saan nak man nga disturboen ta adu ti trabahok.

DIWIG.definition: 1. wry, twisted, contorted: said of the mouth of a person, a jar, a basket, etc. 2. crooked, not straight: said of the way an object is cut. 3. having a wry mouth: said of a person.

DODOL.definition: a kind of pudding made of rice, either ground or pounded into powder, GETTA and sugar.

DODOOMEN.definition: rice near maturity whose grain is already fully formed.

DINOMINGGO.definition: every week, weekly, by the week.

DON.ilok_example: Sir; Mr.: a title of respect, used with the first name. 2. a distinguished man.

DONYA.ilok_example: Madam; Mrs.: a title of respect, used with the first name. 2. a distinguished woman. 3. rat, mouse.

DOOL.definition: to feed, especially by putting the food to the mouth.

DOOM.definition: to eat or chew immature rice or uncooked rice after removing the husk.
to eat or chew: said of immature rice or uncooked rice after removing the husk.

DOOY.definition: wanting attention, care or show of affection: usually said of children.
DOOY.eng_example: You are a child who wants so much attention.

DRAM.definition: drum: a barrellike metal container for oil, etc.

DUBLI.definition: to repeat, to do, say, etc. again.

DUDA.definition: to have doubts, be doubtful, suspicious.

DUGDUG.definition: to decay, decompose, rot, dissolve, melt.

DUGMAM.definition: to cause to fall forward or prone.

DUGMON.definition: nest of a wild boar or a hog.
to wallow, to roll oneself about in an indolent or ungainly manner.
to collect or gather for making a .

DUGUL.definition: a hump, protuberance, swelling; a node.

DUKANG.definition: bulky, piled in a big heap.

DUKINAR.eng_example: Why are you strewing around the clothes?
DUKINAR.ilok_example: Apay nga dukinaren yo dagita lupot?

DUKIT.definition: to reopen a subject, to mention again; to recall, to remind someone of.
DUKIT.eng_example: Don’t mention that again for I have already forgotten it.
DUKIT.ilok_example: Saan mo nga idukit dayta ta nalipatakon.

DUKLUS.eng_example: It was he who attacked me.

DUKO.definition: to recur: said of an ailment, hunger, etc.
DUKO.eng_example: I am worried lest my sickness recurs.
DUKO.ilok_example: Madanaganak no dumuko ti sakit ko.

DUKOL.definition: to produce a hump disclosing its presence; to protrude, jut out.
DUKOL.eng_example: What is that producing a hump on the mat?

DUKOT.definition: to be worried, distressed, uneasy, perturbed, anxious, impatient.

DUKYANG.definition: a kind of small clam found in brooks and rivers.

DULIAN.eng_example: He has not a distinguishing trait.

DULIDUL.definition: to urge, press, insist, or force on (someone).
DULIDUL.eng_example: Don’t force on me that which I don’t like.
DULIDUL.ilok_example: Saan mo nga idulidul kanyak dayta saan ko nga kayat.

DULIN.definition: to hide, stay away from view.
DULIN.eng_example: You hide and I will look for you.

DULIN.definition: to hide or keep away from view (someone or something). - -syn.
to put away, put aside (plates or bedding).

DUMA.definition: to differ, be different, dissimilar, unlike.

DUMADUMA.ilok_example: Nadumaduma nga nateng ti immula da.

DUMDUMA.definition: to be regarded differently, to be distinguishable, to stand out.

DUMUG.definition: to bend or incline the head, to bow; to look down.
DUMUG.eng_example: He looked down when he saw me.

DUMUG.definition: to bend or incline down, to cause to bend or incline down.

DUNG-AW.definition: to wail, lament, mourn aloud which may include singing a dirge.

DUNGDUNG.definition: a very large pot used for cooking rice, meat, vegetables, etc.

DUNGER.definition: to shake the head forward and backward rapidly, to nod rapidly and continuously.
to have the head drop forward involuntarily due to drowsiness, etc.

DUNGET.definition: to cut near or close to the trunk, origin or beginning.
DUNGET.eng_example: It was he who cut close the branches of the tree.
DUNGET.ilok_example: Isu ti nangidunget ti sanga ti kayo.

DUNGIR.definition: to get hurt, injured or bruised.
DUNGIR.eng_example: Don’t run for you might get hurt.
DUNGIR.ilok_example: Saan ka nga agtartaray ta dikanto madungiran.

DUNGNGO.eng_example: I shall love you very, very deeply.

DUNGRIT.definition: filthy, dirty, untidy, especially on the face.

DUNGSO.definition: to crash (oneself or itself) into, to ram (oneself or itself) against, to cause (oneself) to collide with.
DUNGSO.eng_example: Why did you collide with me?

DUNGSO.definition: to crash into, ram against, collide with.
DUNGSO.eng_example: Their vehicle crashed into a post.
DUNGSO.ilok_example: Naidungso diay lugan da ti poste.

DUNGSOL.definition: to use as this (on someone or something), to hit (someone or something) with this.

DUPAG.definition: to repeat, do again, say again.
DUPAG.eng_example: Will you please repeat what you said to me.

DUPIR.definition: to push, shove or move to (a place).
DUPIR.eng_example: Push that bench to that wall.
DUPIR.ilok_example: Idupir mo dayta bangko dita diding.

DUPUDUP.definition: to be, go or come together.
DUPUDUP.eng_example: They came together to buy clothes.
DUPUDUP.ilok_example: Nagdudupudup da nga immay gimmatang ti lupot.

DUREK.definition: to have this: said of the ear.

DURI.definition: spinal column, vertebral column, spine, backbone.

DURUDOR.definition: 1. to put on a spit. 2. to poke with a spit.

DUSAG.definition: to elbow, hit with the elbow.
DUSAG.eng_example: Don’t hit me with your elbow.

DUTDUT.definition: to remove the feather of, to dress (a chicken, etc.).
to extract, draw out, pick off.

DUTOK.ilok_example: Ni Pedro ti dinutokan mi nga presidente.

DUTOK.definition: to be appointed, designated, assigned (as president, etc.).

DINUYDUY.definition: a kind of sweet made of boiled ripe squash mixed with coconut meat and either sugar or salt.

DUYOG.definition: 1. half of coconut shell used as dish. 2. dish.

DUYOK.definition: to produce or cause a sharp or stabbing pain.
DUYOK.eng_example: My stomach ailment is producing again a sharp pain.
DUYOK.ilok_example: Dumuyok manen ti sakit na daytoy tian ko.

DUYOK.eng_example: He stabbed the pig with a sharp knife.
DUYOK.ilok_example: Dinuyok na daydiay baboy ti natirad nga imuko.

DUYOS.definition: that to which one’s feelings, sympathy, etc. flows.
DUYOS.eng_example: It is he to whom my feelings flow.
